[{"id":"VR797914","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows a charged wire parallel to the y axis in an x y coordinate system with the origin labeled P.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR797914.g02.svg\"/></div></div></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">An infinitely long, uniformly charged wire is parallel to the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"y\"><math alttext=\"y\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>y</mi></math></span></span>-axis in an <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"x y\"><math alttext=\"x y\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>x</mi><mi>y</mi></math></span></span> coordinate system, as shown in the figure. The sign of the charge on the wire is unknown. Which of the following statements makes a correct claim about the direction of the electric field <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"vector E sub P\"><math alttext=\"vector E sub P\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><msub><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>E</mi><mo>→</mo></mover><mtext>P</mtext></msub></mstyle></math></span></span> at Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P\"><math alttext=\"P\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></math></span></span>, and provides evidence or reasoning that supports the claim?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR797914_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"vector E sub P\"><math alttext=\"vector E sub P\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><msub><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>E</mi><mo>→</mo></mover><mtext>P</mtext></msub></mstyle></math></span></span> is in the positive or negative <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"x\"><math alttext=\"x\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>x</mi></math></span></span>-direction. The <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"y\"><math alttext=\"y\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>y</mi></math></span></span>-components of field contributions from different locations on the wire cancel, leaving only an <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"x\"><math alttext=\"x\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>x</mi></math></span></span>-component.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"vector E sub P\"><math alttext=\"vector E sub P\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><msub><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>E</mi><mo>→</mo></mover><mtext>P</mtext></msub></mstyle></math></span></span> is in the positive or negative <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"x\"><math alttext=\"x\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>x</mi></math></span></span>-direction. The electric field at a point is directed either toward or away from the nearest location on the charge distribution that produces the field.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"vector E sub P\"><math alttext=\"vector E sub P\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><msub><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>E</mi><mo>→</mo></mover><mtext>P</mtext></msub></mstyle></math></span></span> is in the positive or negative <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"y\"><math alttext=\"y\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>y</mi></math></span></span>-direction. The field of a charge distribution aligns along the direction of the distribution.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"vector E sub P\"><math alttext=\"vector E sub P\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><msub><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>E</mi><mo>→</mo></mover><mtext>P</mtext></msub></mstyle></math></span></span> is in the positive or negative <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"y\"><math alttext=\"y\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>y</mi></math></span></span>-direction. Most locations along the wire are far away and can be considered to contribute strongly to the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"y\"><math alttext=\"y\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>y</mi></math></span></span>-component of the field and negligibly to the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"x\"><math alttext=\"x\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>x</mi></math></span></span>-component.</p>"],"answer":0}]